						<p class="first">For Marie-Helene Colaiezzi (BA ’07, BEd ’08), her love of Laurier began when she was first looking for the perfect university. “I’m from a smaller town and Laurier immediately felt like home,” says Marie-Helene. “I love that it was, and is still, a smaller, more intimate campus. The small class sizes, students being more than a number, the volunteer opportunities and the amazing professors and the relationships you build with them. Laurier has everything I was looking for and it lived up to my expectations.”</p>
						<p>A part of the first cohort to graduate from Laurier’s Faculty of Education and a committed alumni donor, Marie-Helene credits her professional successes to the Bachelor of Education program’s unique structure. “Through the program we work with a school two days a week all year, and then also do our placements there. This is unique and it allows teaching students to build a strong rapport with the school, the host teachers and the students. We become a part of the school life, participating in extra-curricular activities and collaborating on projects. It really sets us up for success on placements and beyond.”</p>
						<div class="captioned-image right-image">
							<img src="images/impact/impact5-marie-helene2.jpg" class="tall-image" alt="Marie-Helene Portrait"/>
							<p class="caption"></p>
						</div>
						<h4 class="spotlight">Since graduating, Marie-Helene has found a number of ways to stay connected to the Laurier community</h4>
						<p>Since graduating, Marie-Helene has found a number of ways to stay connected to the Laurier community. “My financial gift isn’t huge, but I enjoy also giving my time, through the WLUAA [Wilfrid Laurier University Alumni Association] Board of Directors, alumni events, career nights and other activities. I enjoy being back on campus—the nostalgia, yes, but also how much the campus has continued to change excites me. I love the buzz of hearing and seeing the students, of finding opportunities to share my story about finding a job in the community and helping answer their questions of ‘what happens now?’”</p>
						<p>“I’m a part of the Waterloo community. I’m not from Waterloo—I don’t have a growing up connection. My connection is my post-secondary experience at Laurier, and it was a great experience. So my roots in the community started through Laurier, and it just makes sense to give back to Laurier any way I can to foster and build up my community as a whole.”</p>
